The '''KOV-14 Fortezza Plus''' is a US [[National Security Agency]]-approved [[PC card]] which provides [[cryptography|encryption]] functions and key storage to the [[Secure Terminal Equipment]] and other devices.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.allbusiness.com/government/government-bodies-offices/5037799-1.html| title=Department of Defense Awards Enhanced Crypto Card Development Contract to SafeNet| work=Business Wire| date=2005-03-14| accessdate=2009-12-21}}</ref> It is a [[tamper-resistant]] module based on the [[Mykotronx]] [[Krypton (microchip)|Krypton chip]], including all of the cryptographic functionality of the original [[Fortezza]] card plus the [[Type 1 encryption|Type 1]] algorithms/protocols [[BATON]] and [[Firefly (protocol)|Firefly]], the [[Secure Data Network System|SDNS]] signature algorithm, and the [[STU-III]] protocol. It was developed by Mykotronx as part of the NSA's [[MISSI]] program. As of 2008, the KOV-14 is beginning to be phased out and replaced by the backwards compatible [[KSV-21]] PC card. <ref>{{cite web |url = https://e-center.doe.gov/iips/busopor.nsf/1be0f2271893ba198525644b006bc0be/90f4fe189eda9e00852574450069aac2?OpenDocument |title = Solicitation DE-AI52-08NA28817 |author = Information Technology Department of the National Nuclear Security Administration |publisher = [[United States Department of Energy|DoE]] Industry Interactive Procurement System |accessdate = 2009-12-21 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
