{{Infobox scientist | name = Kathrin Bringmann | image = Mahlburg Bringmann.jpg<!--(as myimage.jpg, no 'File:')--> | image_size = | alt = | caption = [[Karl Mahlburg]] (left) and Kathrin Bringmann (2009) | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1977|5|8|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Münster]], [[Germany]] | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = [[Germany|German]] | fields = [[Mathematics]] | workplaces = [[University of Cologne]] | alma_mater = [[University of Heidelberg]] | doctoral_advisor = {{Interlanguage link multi|Winfried Kohnen|de}} | doctoral_students = | known_for = | awards = [[SASTRA Ramanujan Prize]] (2009) }}
'''Kathrin Bringmann''' (born 8 May 1977) is a German [[number theorist]] in the [[University of Cologne]], [[Germany]], who has made fundamental contributions to the theory of [[mock theta function]]s.
==Education and career== Kathrin Bringmann was born on 8 May 1977, in [[Münster|Muenster]], [[Germany]]. She passed the State Examinations in Mathematics and Theology at the [[University of Würzburg]], Germany, in 2002, and obtained a Diploma in Mathematics at [[Würzburg]] in 2003. She received PhD in 2004 from [[University of Heidelberg]] under the supervision of {{Interlanguage link multi|Winfried Kohnen|de}}.
During 2004–07, she was [[Edward Burr Van Vleck]] Assistant Professor with the [[University of Wisconsin]] where she began her collaboration with [[Ken Ono]]. After briefly serving as an Assistant Professor at the [[University of Minnesota]], she joined the [[University of Cologne]], Germany, as Professor.
==Recognition== Bringmann has been awarded the Alfried Krupp-Förderpreis for Young Professors, a one-million-Euro prize instituted by the [[Alfried Krupp von Bohlen und Halbach Foundation]]. She is the third mathematician to win this prize.<ref>[http://www.ams.org/news/home-news.html#bringmann-krupp Bringmann Receives One Million Euro Krupp Prize]</ref> She has also been awarded the [[SASTRA Ramanujan Prize]] in 2009 for her contributions to "areas of mathematics influenced by the genius [[Srinivasa Ramanujan]]."<ref>[http://www.sastra.edu/mnews/2009/sep/Ramanujan_Award.htm German Professor bags SASTRA Ramanujan Award for 2009] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091004105145/http://www.sastra.edu/mnews/2009/sep/Ramanujan_Award.htm |date=2009-10-04 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.ams.org/news/home-news.html#sastra-09 Bringmann to Receive 2009 SASTRA Ramanujan Prize]</ref>
She was the Emmy Noether Lecturer of the [[German Mathematical Society]] in 2015.<ref>{{citation|url=https://www.mathematik.de/dmv/preise-auszeichnungen|title=Preise und Auszeichnungen|publisher=[[German Mathematical Society]]|language=German|accessdate=2018-11-05}}</ref>
