'''Tomasz Łuczak''' (born 13 March 1963 in [[Poznań]])<ref>Joseph A., Mignot F., Murat F., Prum B., Rentschler R. (1994.) [https://books.google.com/books?id=hLrptG7XxvwC&pg=PR43 ''First [[European Congress of Mathematics]] Paris, July 6–10, 1992: Vol. 1: Invited Lectures''], Nelson Thornes.</ref> is a [[Poland|Polish]] [[mathematician]] and [[professor]] at [[Adam Mickiewicz University in Poznań]] and [[Emory University]]. His main field of research is [[combinatorics]], specifically [[discrete mathematics|discrete]] [[Mathematical structure|structures]], such as [[random graph]]s, and their [[chromatic number]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Łuczak |first=Tomasz |authormask=3 |title=The chromatic number of random graphs |journal=Combinatorica |volume=11 |issue=1 |year=1991 |pages=45–54 |doi=10.1007/BF01375472 }}</ref>
Under supervision of [[Michał Karoński]], Łuczak earned his doctorate at Adam Mickiewicz University in Poznań in 1987.<ref>{{MathGenealogy |id=154490 }}</ref> In 1992, he was awarded the [[EMS Prize]] and in 1997 he received the prestigious [[Prize of the Foundation for Polish Science]] for his work on the theory of [[discrete mathematics|random discrete structures]].
